About Me

Engineering tomorrow's solutions, today.

My passion for engineering started early: assembling LEGO sets, helping put together IKEA furniture, seeing every task as a puzzle waiting to be solved. This curiosity led me to join my school's robotics team in fourth grade, and I've been building ever since.

Currently, I'm a Mechanical Engineering student at Northeastern University, where I've sharpened my skills through hands-on co-op experiences at Rheem Manufacturing and SharkNinja. I specialize in product design, CAD modeling, and bringing concepts from sketch to prototype.

Finding the Problem: Low Ceiling Access

Traditional top-mounted anode rods are difficult to replace in homes with low ceilings. Homeowners can't pull the long rod straight up out of the tank.

Researching: 300+ Part Tank Assembly

Obtained complete water tank assembly from CAD team. Studied internal components including heating elements, sensors, and baffles to identify viable side-mounting positions.

Final Design: 3 Optimal Mounting Positions

Designed adapter fixtures for 3 side-mounting positions that avoid heating elements while ensuring proper corrosion protection coverage throughout the tank.

R&D Engineering

Side-Mounted Anode Rod

Designed adapter fixtures enabling side-mounted anode rod installation for homes with low ceilings. Analyzed a 300+ part water tank assembly to identify 3 optimal mounting positions that avoid internal heating elements while maintaining corrosion protection.

SN

SharkNinja

NPD Engineer Co-op, Home Environment January June 2025

Finding the Issue: Vibration & Sound Testing

Ran fans offsite until abnormal buzzing appeared on boost mode. Used sound meters and vibration meters to quantify the issue causing negative consumer reviews.

Diagnosing: Dyson Motor Transplant

Disassembled Dyson AM07 and transplanted its motor/impeller into TurboBlade housing with custom CAD adapters. Dyson motor had no noise, which confirmed our motor was the issue.

Fixing: Motor & Impeller Balancing

Built custom test rigs with DAQ balancing software. Used CT scans to root-cause imbalance. Fixed by shaving off parts of the impeller to achieve proper balance.

Product Testing & Problem Solving

Shark TurboBlade Fan

Diagnosed and resolved vibration issues causing loud buzzing on boost mode that led to negative consumer reviews. Identified the root cause by transplanting a Dyson motor to isolate the problem, then fixed it through motor/impeller balancing using DAQ systems and CT scanning.

DAQ Systems CT Scanning Vibration Analysis 3D Printing SOLIDWORKS
Finding the Issue: Drape Test Failure

Conducted drape tests by covering the heating element with a towel. The thermostat failed to trip, causing plastic externals to overheat and melt, blocking product launch.

Diagnosing: Thermal Camera Analysis

Used FLIR thermal cameras to map heat distribution. Found that the thermostat location didn't get hot enough during drape tests to trip before plastic deformation occurred.

Fixing: DAQ Testing & Thermostat Relocation

Used DAQ thermocouples to test new locations and validate temperatures. Relocated thermostat to an area that reached trip temperature before deformation, solving the safety issue.

Critical Safety Resolution

TurboBlade + Heat

Resolved a critical thermostat failure blocking tower heater launch. During drape tests, the thermostat wasn't tripping before plastic deformation. Used thermal imaging to identify the root cause and DAQ thermocouples to validate a new thermostat location that trips before any damage occurs.

Thermal Imaging DAQ Systems Thermocouples Safety Testing
NEU

Capstone Project

Northeastern University Senior Design 2025

Design Overview

Our adjustable resistance band features an elastic band (25-50 lbs), clasps connecting strap and band, strap roll-up mechanism, and internal spring gear mechanism (0-25 lbs). Materials include threaded latex, PLA filament, steel bearings, and polypropylene webbing.

The Problem: Gap in the Market

Existing resistance equipment requires swapping bands or lacks portability. We identified a need for a lightweight, intuitive, and inexpensive adjustable resistance band system.

Elastic Band & Clasps

Threaded latex band (25-50 lbs) with PLA clasps featuring backstitch sewing. Acts as safety mechanism that prevents system overload at maximum extension.

Spooling Mechanism

Polypropylene webbing (290 lbs working load, 0.75mm thick) wraps around spool. Ball bearings reduce friction while rollers and guides prevent twisting and sideways migration.

Keying Mechanism

304 stainless steel locking gears with machined aluminum axle and A2 tool steel key pin. Spring-loaded bearing balls enable gear connection/disconnection for resistance selection.

Selector Mechanism

PLA+ knurled dial with detented positions for tactile feedback. Snail wheel sets horizontal position while wedge pulls key pin to correct height for resistance selection.

Spring Stack

5 torsion spring modules in parallel with internal ratchet preventing reverse loading. Embedded metal gear teeth provide max torque of 8.8 in*lbs over 3 rotations maximum extension.

FEA & Testing

Performed FEA on PLA clasps. Initial max stress 3203 psi at corner (fracture risk). Redesigned with rounded corners, reduced to 2382 psi. Force testing confirmed linear 5-50 lb resistance.

Senior Design

Adjustable Resistance Bands

Designed a lightweight, portable resistance band system capable of varying resistance from 5-50 lbs without swapping bands. Engineered custom mechanisms including spooling system, keying assembly with spring-loaded pins, selector dial, and parallel torsion spring stack. Validated design through FEA analysis and force testing.

SOLIDWORKS FEA 3D Printing (PLA+) Gear Design Spring Characterization Instron Testing
